<doc id="398931" wikidata="Q1003225" url="?curid=398931" title="Measure-preserving dynamical system">
<text>In mathematics, a measure-preserving dynamical system is an object of study in the abstract formulation of dynamical systems, and ergodic theory in particular. Measure-preserving systems obey the Poincaré recurrence theorem, and are a special case of conservative systems. They provide the formal, mathematical basis for a broad range of physical systems, and, in particular, many systems from classical mechanics (in particular, most non-dissipative systems) as well as systems in thermodynamic equilibrium.

==Definition==
A measure-preserving dynamical system is defined as a probability space and a measure-preserving transformation on it. In more detail, it is a system

:formula_1

with the following structure:

*formula_2 is a set,
*formula_3 is a σ-algebra over formula_2,
*formula_5 is a probability measure, so that formula_6, and formula_7,
*formula_8 is a measurable transformation which preserves the measure formula_9, i.e., formula_10.

==Discussion==
One may ask why the measure preserving transformation is defined in terms of the inverse formula_11 instead of the forward transformation formula_12. This can be understood intuitively. 

Consider the typical measure on the unit interval formula_13, and a map formula_14. This is the Bernoulli map. Now, distribute an even layer of paint on the unit interval formula_13, and then map the paint forward. The paint on the formula_16 half is spread thinly over all of formula_13, and the paint on the formula_18 half as well. The two layers of thin paint, layered together, recreates the exact same paint thickness.

More generally, the paint that would arrive at subset formula_19 comes from the subset formula_20. For the paint thickness to remain unchanged (measure-preserving), the mass of incoming paint should be the same: formula_21.

Consider a mapping formula_22 of power sets:
:formula_23
Consider now the special case of maps formula_22 which preserve intersections, unions and complements (so that it is a map of Borel sets) and also sends formula_2 to formula_2 (because we want it to be conservative). Every such conservative, Borel-preserving map can be specified by some surjective map formula_27 by writing formula_28. Of course, one could also define formula_29, but this is not enough to specify all such possible maps formula_22. That is, conservative, Borel-preserving maps formula_22 cannot, in general, be written in the form formula_32.

formula_33 has the form of a pushforward, whereas formula_34 is generically called a pullback. Almost all properties and behaviors of dynamical systems are defined in terms of the pushforward. For example, the transfer operator is defined in terms of the pushforward of the transformation map formula_35; the measure formula_9 can now be understood as an invariant measure; it is just the Frobenius–Perron eigenvector of the transfer operator (recall, the FP eigenvector is the largest eigenvector of a matrix; in this case it is the eigenvector which has the eigenvalue one: the invariant measure.)

There are two classification problems of interest. One, discussed below, fixes formula_37 and asks about the isomorphism classes of a transformation map formula_35. The other, discussed in transfer operator, fixes formula_39 and formula_35, and asks about maps formula_9 that are measure-like. Measure-like, in that they preserve the Borel properties, but are no longer invariant; they are in general dissipative and so give insights into dissipative systems and the route to equilibrium.

In terms of physics, the measure-preserving dynamical system formula_1 often describes a physical system that is in equilibrium, for example, thermodynamic equilibrium. One might ask: how did it get that way? Often, the answer is by stirring, mixing, turbulence, thermalization or other such processes. If a transformation map formula_35 describes this stirring, mixing, etc. then the system formula_1 is all that is left, after all of the transient modes have decayed away. The transient modes are precisely those eigenvectors of the transfer operator that have eigenvalue less than one; the invariant measure formula_9 is the one mode that does not decay away. The rate of decay of the transient modes are given by (the logarithm of) their eigenvalues; the eigenvalue one corresponds to infinite half-life.

==Informal example==
The microcanonical ensemble from physics provides an informal example. Consider, for example, a fluid, gas or plasma in a box of width, length and height formula_46 consisting of formula_47 atoms. A single atom in that box might be anywhere, having arbitrary velocity; it would be represented by a single point in formula_48 A given collection of formula_47 atoms would then be a &quot;single point&quot; somewhere in the space formula_50 The &quot;ensemble&quot; is the collection of all such points, that is, the collection of all such possible boxes (of which there are an uncountably-infinite number). This ensemble of all-possible-boxes is the space formula_2 above.

In the case of an ideal gas, the measure formula_9 is given by the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution. It is a product measure, in that if formula_53 is the probability of atom formula_54 having position and velocity formula_55, then, for formula_47 atoms, the probability is the product of formula_47 of these. This measure is understood to apply to the ensemble. So, for example, one of the possible boxes in the ensemble has all of the atoms on one side of the box. One can compute the likelihood of this, in the Maxwell–Boltzmann measure. It will be enormously tiny, of order formula_58 Of all possible boxes in the ensemble, this is a ridiculously small fraction.

The only reason that this is an &quot;informal example&quot; is because writing down the transition function formula_35 is difficult, and, even if written down, it is hard to perform practical computations with it. Difficulties are compounded if there are interactions between the particles themselves, like a van der Waals interaction or some other interaction suitable for a liquid or a plasma; in such cases, the invariant measure is no longer the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution. The art of physics is finding reasonable approximations.

This system does exhibit one key idea from the classification of measure-preserving dynamical systems: two ensembles, having different temperatures, are inequivalent. The entropy for a given canonical ensemble depends on its temperature; as physical systems, it is &quot;obvious&quot; that when the temperatures differ, so do the systems. This holds in general: systems with different entropy are not isomorphic.

==Examples==
Example of a ([[Lebesgue measure]]) preserving map: &quot;T&quot; : [0,1) → [0,1), formula_60 Unlike the informal example above, the examples below are sufficiently well-defined and tractable that explicit, formal computations can be performed.

* μ could be the normalized angle measure dθ/2π on the unit circle, and &quot;T&quot; a rotation. See equidistribution theorem;
* the Bernoulli scheme;
* the interval exchange transformation;
* with the definition of an appropriate measure, a subshift of finite type;
* the base flow of a random dynamical system;
* the flow of a Hamiltonian vector field on the tangent bundle of a closed connected smooth manifold is measure-preserving (using the measure induced on the Borel sets by the symplectic volume form) by Liouville&#x27;s theorem (Hamiltonian);
* for certain maps and Markov processes, the Krylov–Bogolyubov theorem establishes the existence of a suitable measure to form a measure-preserving dynamical system.

==Generalization to groups and monoids==
The definition of a measure-preserving dynamical system can be generalized to the case in which &quot;T&quot; is not a single transformation that is iterated to give the dynamics of the system, but instead is a monoid (or even a group, in which case we have the action of a group upon the given probability space) of transformations &quot;Ts&quot; : &quot;X&quot; → &quot;X&quot; parametrized by &quot;s&quot; ∈ Z (or R, or N ∪ {0}, or [0, +∞)), where each transformation &quot;Ts&quot; satisfies the same requirements as &quot;T&quot; above. In particular, the transformations obey the rules:
* formula_61, the identity function on &quot;X&quot;;
* formula_62, whenever all the terms are well-defined;
* formula_63, whenever all the terms are well-defined.

The earlier, simpler case fits into this framework by defining &quot;Ts&quot; = &quot;Ts&quot; for &quot;s&quot; ∈ N.

==Homomorphisms==
The concept of a homomorphism and an isomorphism may be defined.

Consider two dynamical systems formula_64 and formula_65. Then a mapping

:formula_66

is a homomorphism of dynamical systems if it satisfies the following three properties:

# The map formula_67 is measurable.
# For each formula_68, one has formula_69.
# For formula_9-almost all formula_71, one has formula_72.

The system formula_65 is then called a factor of formula_64.

The map formula_75 is an isomorphism of dynamical systems if, in addition, there exists another mapping

:formula_76

that is also a homomorphism, which satisfies

# for formula_9-almost all formula_71, one has formula_79;
# for formula_80-almost all formula_81, one has formula_82.

Hence, one may form a category of dynamical systems and their homomorphisms.

==Generic points==
A point &quot;x&quot; ∈ &quot;X&quot; is called a generic point if the orbit of the point is distributed uniformly according to the measure.

==Symbolic names and generators==
Consider a dynamical system formula_83, and let &quot;Q&quot; = {&quot;Q&quot;1, ..., &quot;Qk&quot;} be a partition of &quot;X&quot; into &quot;k&quot; measurable pair-wise disjoint sets. Given a point &quot;x&quot; ∈ &quot;X&quot;, clearly &quot;x&quot; belongs to only one of the &quot;Qi&quot;. Similarly, the iterated point &quot;Tnx&quot; can belong to only one of the parts as well. The symbolic name of &quot;x&quot;, with regards to the partition &quot;Q&quot;, is the sequence of integers {&quot;a&quot;&quot;n&quot;} such that

:formula_84

The set of symbolic names with respect to a partition is called the symbolic dynamics of the dynamical system. A partition &quot;Q&quot; is called a generator or generating partition if μ-almost every point &quot;x&quot; has a unique symbolic name.

==Operations on partitions==
Given a partition Q = {&quot;Q&quot;1, ..., &quot;Q&quot;&quot;k&quot;} and a dynamical system formula_83, define the &quot;T&quot;-pullback of &quot;Q&quot; as

:formula_86

Further, given two partitions &quot;Q&quot; = {&quot;Q&quot;1, ..., &quot;Qk&quot;} and &quot;R&quot; = {&quot;R&quot;1, ..., &quot;R&quot;&quot;m&quot;}, define their refinement as

:formula_87

With these two constructs, the &quot;refinement of an iterated pullback&quot; is defined as

:formula_88

which plays crucial role in the construction of the measure-theoretic entropy of a dynamical system.

==Measure-theoretic entropy==

The entropy of a partition formula_89 is defined as

:formula_90

The measure-theoretic entropy of a dynamical system formula_83 with respect to a partition &quot;Q&quot; = {&quot;Q&quot;1, ..., &quot;Q&quot;&quot;k&quot;} is then defined as

:formula_92

Finally, the Kolmogorov–Sinai metric or measure-theoretic entropy of a dynamical system formula_93 is defined as

:formula_94

where the supremum is taken over all finite measurable partitions. A theorem of Yakov Sinai in 1959 shows that the supremum is actually obtained on partitions that are generators. Thus, for example, the entropy of the Bernoulli process is log 2, since almost every real number has a unique binary expansion. That is, one may partition the unit interval into the intervals [0, 1/2) and [1/2, 1]. Every real number &quot;x&quot; is either less than 1/2 or not; and likewise so is the fractional part of 2&quot;n&quot;&quot;x&quot;.

If the space &quot;X&quot; is compact and endowed with a topology, or is a metric space, then the topological entropy may also be defined.

If formula_35 is an ergodic, piecewise expanding, and Markov on formula_96, and formula_9 is absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure, then we have the Rokhlin formula (section 4.3 and section 12.3 ):formula_98This allows calculation of entropy of many interval maps, such as the logistic map.

Ergodic means that formula_99 implies formula_100 has full measure or zero measure. Piecewise expanding and Markov means that there is a partition of formula_2 into finitely many open intervals, such that for some formula_102, formula_103 on each open interval. Markov means that for each formula_104 from those open intervals, either formula_105 or formula_106.

==Classification and anti-classification theorems==
One of the primary activities in the study of measure-preserving systems is their classification according to their properties. That is, let formula_37 be a measure space, and let formula_108 be the set of all measure preserving systems formula_1. An isomorphism formula_110 of two transformations formula_111 defines an equivalence relation formula_112 The goal is then to describe the relation formula_113. A number of classification theorems have been obtained; but quite interestingly, a number of anti-classification theorems have been found as well. The anti-classification theorems state that there are more than a countable number of isomorphism classes, and that a countable amount of information is not sufficient to classify isomorphisms.

The first anti-classification theorem, due to Hjorth, states that if formula_108 is endowed with the weak topology, then the set formula_113 is not a Borel set. There are a variety of other anti-classification results. For example, replacing isomorphism with Kakutani equivalence, it can be shown that there are uncountably many non-Kakutani equivalent ergodic measure-preserving transformations of each entropy type.

These stand in contrast to the classification theorems. These include:
* Ergodic measure-preserving transformations with a pure point spectrum have been classified.
* Bernoulli shifts are classified by their metric entropy. See Ornstein theory for more.

